senses.ex: The meal is not complete without dessert.

Tips.title: Not Optional
Tips.description: Anything 'complete' must include every necessary part.
Tips.example: A complete set of tools comes with screwdrivers, wrenches, and hammers.

senses.ex: The construction of the building is complete.

Tips.title: End of Process
Tips.description: 'Complete' implies that an activity or process has reached its end.
Tips.example: Sign here to indicate the paperwork is complete.

senses.ex: Complete your homework before you go outside.

Tips.title: Call to Action
Tips.description: 'Complete' can be a directive meaning 'do this task to the end'.
Tips.example: Please complete the survey after the presentation.

senses.ex: The new sofa completes the living room.

Tips.title: Adds the Final Touch
Tips.description: 'Complete' suggests that an addition transforms something into its best or final form.
Tips.example: A vase of flowers completed the room’s decor.

senses.ex: It was a complete shock when I heard the news.

Tips.title: Intensifying Effect
Tips.description: Describes something as being extreme or to the maximum degree.
Tips.example: She gave a complete answer to every question.

senses.de: competent or proficient in all respects
senses.ex: He is a complete professional when it comes to his work.

Tips.title: Skill Implication
Tips.description: Shows that a person can do all parts of a task or job very well.
Tips.example: As a complete mechanic, she can repair engines and bodywork.

Absolute.wordDefinition:
Absolute means something that is total, complete and not affected by any other factors. For example, "The law gave her absolute control over her property." It emphasizes the pure and ultimate state of something.

In simpler terms, absolute focuses on the quality, while complete focuses on the quantity of something. Both words can be used in different situations, but absolute is more suitable when emphasizing the ultimate and pure state of something, whereas complete is more suitable when emphasizing that there is nothing missing or unfinished.

Comprehensive.wordDefinition:
Comprehensive means that something covers or includes all possible aspects or details, leaving nothing out.

A comprehensive report on a topic would include every detail, no matter how small.

To put it simply, complete means having all the parts needed, while comprehensive means having all the parts and every tiny detail included.

Entire.wordDefinition:
Complete means that something has all its necessary parts or elements, so it is finished or perfect. It usually refers to a specific thing or task that has been done or fulfilled entirely.

Entire means that something is whole or complete in itself. It refers to the entirety of something, and not just a part of it.

For instance, if you say, "I read the entire book," it means you have read the whole book from cover to cover, not just a few chapters.

If a sign says, "No parking in the entire lot," it means that there is no parking allowed in any part of the parking lot.

Complete refers to a specific thing or task that has been done entirely, while entire refers to the wholeness of something itself.

Exhaustive.wordDefinition:
Exhaustive means everything that is available or possible has been considered or examined.

It is used when referring to a thorough search or investigation that leaves no stone unturned. For example, an exhaustive search for a missing pet would involve looking in every possible location and asking everyone in the area.

Complete refers to having all necessary components, while exhaustive refers to a thorough and comprehensive investigation or search.

Finish.wordDefinition:
While both words refer to reaching the end of something, complete implies fulfilling or accomplishing a task, whereas finish refers specifically to ending a task.

For example, if you complete a project, you have successfully done everything necessary to finish it, but if you finish a project, you may not have necessarily completed all the required steps.

Complete is used to emphasize the achievement of a goal, while finish merely states that an activity has come to an end.

For example, you can complete a puzzle, a marathon, or a degree, but you wouldn't say you finished them because that implies a lack of effort or challenge.

You can finish a meal, a book, or a car ride, as those are activities that have a clear end point.

Full.wordDefinition:
Full usually means that something has reached its maximum capacity or potential. It implies that no more can be added without spilling over.

For instance, if you pour water into a glass until it reaches the brim, you can say that the glass is full.

Complete is used to indicate that something has reached a final state, while full is used to indicate that something has reached maximum capacity.

Intact.wordDefinition:
Intact means something is undamaged or unbroken, and it hasn't lost anything essential. For instance, a vase can be intact and yet be incomplete, such as a vase with a missing handle.

Intact is applicable when something is still perfect in whole but has minor repairs or discrepancies.

Perfect.wordDefinition:
Perfect means that something is flawless or without any faults or mistakes. For example, a person can strive for perfect performance on a test, or an artwork can be considered perfect if it is visually flawless.

Complete refers to having all necessary parts or elements, while perfect refers to being without any flaws. Both words are applicable in different contexts depending on the situation.

Thorough.wordDefinition:
Thorough means doing something with great care, attention to detail, and completeness. For example, a thorough cleaning means that every nook and cranny has been cleaned.

Thorough is applicable whenever you want to describe something that has been done with great attention to detail or completeness.

Total.wordDefinition:
The words complete and total are very similar in meaning, but there are some subtle differences in their usage.

Total, on the other hand, refers to the sum or entirety of something. For example, if you add up the total amount of money you spent on a vacation, it means you are looking at the entire sum of money you spent, not just parts of it.

If you have a total of 10 apples, it means you have 10 apples in total, not some other number.

So, while the two words are pretty similar, complete implies a sense of finishing or wholeness, while total implies a sense of adding everything up.
